flowRoot.flowPara: Modelling the effects of selective constraints on population life history phenomena.
Ansel George

Each state represents the age of an organism with lifespan λ. Each timestep, individuals in each state move to the next state, with survival probability lx = 1-dx, and offspring are produced by individuals between states α and ω with litter sizes bx.

All populations have intrinsic reproductive capacities necessary to sustain and expand themselves over time. The precise nature of these capacities differs from population to population and are products their evolutionary histories. One measure of these differences is the frequency distribution of ages across the population [1].

The following is an exercise to determine whether selective pressures, modelled as various survival functions, can drive populations toward particular demographic histories that maximize their intrinsic growth rates.

L is the survival matrix for transitoning from one generation to the next (non-zero along superdiagonal), and B is the birth matrix used to generate the the offspring that will population the 0 state. The largest eigenvalue of (L+B) corresponds to the intrinsic growth rate of the population, and its eigenvector (scaled) corresponds to the stationary frequency distribution.

Without constraint, populations can maximize their growth rates by entering fertility earlier, extending it later, and also by increasing litter size. This idealization is not in reality realizable. The simulations on the right show age frequency distributions and r curves for each parameter (b, α, ω, and s) given the others held constant. Defaults values are b=5, α=20, ω=30, and s=1.
Observations:
1. Populations that are able to produce high litter sizes earlier will have greater intrinsic growth rates.
2. It is more effective to begin reproduction earlier than extend fertility in order to increase population growth.
3. A strong (s>1) reproductive constraint will favor small litter sizes.

4. The growth function is relatively flat at large values of ω and α, so populations can vary considerably in this regime and have similar intrinsic growth. These populations will also have lower growth rates and stationary age distributions that skew more heavily toward older individuals.
5. Similar results are obtained from survival functions that skew respectively towards low survival for young or old individuals. (not shown)
